title: For Sale/Trade:  8mm Hakim Semi-Auto
postcontent:
8mm Hakim semi-auto for sale or trade. Will take partial trades.

The Hakim was originally designed by Sweden and produced as the AG-42 Ljungman for the Swedish Army. The tooling and design were later sold to Egypt, and the Hakim was produced there during the 1950s and 1960s. The gas operated system is adjustable by use of a special tool on a valve at the front of the gas tube. This rifle is direct impingement like an AR. Has a Tokarev-pattern tipping bolt system like the SKS and FN49.
Only about 70,000 of these rifles were ever made and only a couple thousand ever made it to the US.

This particular rifle is in good mechanical shape. Bore and crown are very good. The rifle functions as it should using Yugo FMJ. I've put about 125 rounds downrange since I've had it and find it to be very accurate. Probably in large part due to the excellent muzzle break which helps with recoil.
The stock has some dings, but could be cleaned up if you want to refinish it. I don't alter milsurp rifles for fear of hurting their value or damaging them.
The rifle uses detachable box mags, but is really meant to be fed by stripper clips. One ten round mag is included. MG-13 mags can be modified to work with this rifle. They come up on gunbroker every once in a while if you don't want to mod one yourself.
Also have about 100 or so rounds of Yugo FMJ to go with it.

Price is firm. Will not ship. Buyer must sign receipt.

title: For Sale/Trade:  M24 Finnish Mosin Nagant
postcontent:
I have an M24 Finn Mosin for sale.
Of all the Mosins, the Finnish rebuilds are the best, and of those the M24 is probably the rarest. 
These were built for the Civil Guard (called the "Lotta Svard") out of original Russian M91 hex receiver rifles. The action is bedded, the horrible front sight was replaced with a blade front post, and new heavy barrels made by Bohler-Stahl of Germany were installed. These were only produced from Russian captures from 1924 to 1928. Productions numbers are only about 8000 produced.

The good news is that the stock is fantastic. It looks great. The bore is clearly surplus condition, but not bad at all, and the crown is not bad either.
The bad news is that whoever had this rifle before me removed and lost the upper handguard and the entire rear sight. I imagine this was to mount a scope since the rear sight mounting bracket is basically a 3/8 dovetail mount. If you wanted to buy this for a shooter, you could put a scope back on it with no problem.
There is also a problem with the trigger. It wont set when the bolt is pulled back and as a result the bolt doesn't stay cocked. I don't know enough about Mosins to guess why this is happening, but Mosin parts are cheap online, especially common trigger parts. If I had to guess I'd say the sear is worn our or broken. You can get one for less than 10 bucks online. 
The handguards and the sight pieces cost a little more, but they can be taken from Russian M91's, and don't have to be Finn specific.
In excellent shape, these rifles generally go for $500 or more, but I admit this one has problems, so I am asking $220. It's entirely fixable if you want to put the work into it. If you don't, the trigger could be fixed and it would be a good shooter with a scope set-up. The Finn Mosins are known for their accuracy, and between the bedding and heavy barrel, I assume this one would probably be a tack driver.

More pics upon request. Will not ship.

title: For Sale/Trade:  M1 Carbine - IBM Corp - Very Nice with extras
postcontent: For sale is a very nice IBM M1 carbine. Serial number is 37120XX which indicates manufacture between January and March 1944. It was a DCM rifle from years ago and I've had it for about 7 years. There are no import marks! There is only one part that I know is a replacement and that's the late war, swing type safety. There may be more parts but I'm not sure. I have not changed or altered the rifle except for adding the sling and mag pouch. Finish and wear is even and good on all metal parts and the wood is solid with a few dings and bruises. Barrel is marked IBM Corp and dated 10-43.  Bore looks crisp and the muzzle passes the "bullet test".  Stock is marked J-LB with ordnance stamp.  This rifle comes with a correct magazine stock pouch dated 1943, period sling, and three GI 15 round magazines (one is correct IBM). I'll also include a copy of "The M1 Carbine Owner's Guide" by Ruth & Duff. This is a great, collectable piece of history. I'm selling this for $850. Feel free to ask questions. Serious inquiries only. No ammo included in this sale.  Thanks.

For high volume, dirt cheap practice or plinking with a centerfire pistol, few accessories are as useful or cost effective as a 22 rimfire conversion kit. This Tactical Solutions kit is a finely crafted, drop-in slide replacement for America's favorite sidearm, the Model 1911. Engineered to fit Government or Commander sized frames, these machined steel units come complete with a 4.5" barrel, firing pin overtravel stop, adjustable sights, integral full-length optic rail and 10-round aluminum magazine. Installed on the pistol's frame, this conversion kit maintains the feel and profile of its centerfire counterpart, providing the user with a familiar grip angle and operating controls for economical, yet useful and realistic practice. The kit is compatible with single-stack or STI wide-body frame designs with the appropriate magazine inserted. The 10-round magazines lock the slide to the rear when depleted, a unique attribute that is often overlooked on rimfire conversions.
